    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#name": [
      {
        "@value": "Susana SolÃ­s PÃ©rez"
      },
      {
        "@value": "Tineke Strik,"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "@id": "https://w3id.org/deliberation/resource/contribution_386",
    "@type": [
      "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#Contribution"
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#identifier": [
      {
        "@value": "contribution_386"
      }
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#madeBy": [
      {
        "@id": "https://w3id.org/deliberation/resource/participant_275"
      },
      {
        "@id": "https://w3id.org/deliberation/resource/participant_253"
      }
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#text": [
      {
        "@value": "It is astonishing to find ourselves discussing the impact of both Putin and a US President in the same breath, but a fact is a fact. For the sake of future generations, we must invest in our industries, in our defence, in infrastructure and cybersecurity capacity, ensuring our societies are robust and resilient.\nMoreover, we must broaden our alliance beyond the traditional transatlantic relations. While the partnership with the US is still important, Europe should also strengthen ties with states like the UK, Canada, Brazil, Mexico, India, Japan and countries across Africa. The future of global security, of course, depends on our strength, but it also depends on our cooperation with states with shared values and interests."
      },
      {
        "@value": "Russian LNG imports into EU have increased recently, according to some reports. This is not merely a statistical anomaly; it is a strategic vulnerability. Exemptions for pipeline crude oil and the insidious refining loophole continue to funnel vital revenue into Russia.\nLet us be clear: we cannot credibly rearm Europe while our energy dependence fuels the very aggression we seek to deter."
      }
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#timestamp": [
      {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime",
        "@value": "2025-03-11T19:28:54"
      },
      {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime",
        "@value": "2025-03-12T19:54:20"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "@id": "https://w3id.org/deliberation/resource/contribution_363",
    "@type": [
      "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#Contribution"
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#identifier": [
      {
        "@value": "contribution_363"
      }
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#madeBy": [
      {
        "@id": "https://w3id.org/deliberation/resource/participant_1"
      },
      {
        "@id": "https://w3id.org/deliberation/resource/participant_265"
      }
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#text": [
      {
        "@value": ""
      },
      {
        "@value": "Ukraine’s reconstruction costs are now estimated at €383 billion, and they continue to rise as Russia’s brutal war of destruction persists. Meanwhile, Russia’s Central Bank assets frozen in the EU and G7 amount to approximately €300 billion. These funds rightfully belong to the victims of this war—not to the regime that launched it. Seizing even a portion of these assets would provide significant relief for Ukraine’s rebuilding efforts, without shifting the financial burden onto Western taxpayers.\nDirecting tax revenues from frozen Russian assets to Ukraine sets an example of how these funds can be mobilized for justice. But this is not enough—we need a coordinated effort to seize the principal assets themselves.\nEurope must act. Justice demands action. Russia must pay for the devastation it has caused.\nSeize Russia’s frozen assets and ensure they serve Ukraine’s recovery."
      }
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#timestamp": [
      {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime",
        "@value": "2025-03-11T18:59:10"
      }
    ]
  },
