  {
    "@id": "https://w3id.org/deliberation/resource/contribution_236",
    "@type": [
      "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#Contribution"
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#identifier": [
      {
        "@value": "contribution_236"
      }
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#madeBy": [
      {
        "@id": "https://w3id.org/deliberation/resource/participant_144"
      },
      {
        "@id": "https://w3id.org/deliberation/resource/participant_188"
      }
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#text": [
      {
        "@value": "One should not forget about the other proposal, which is the reform of the EU pharmaceutical legislation. This House has already managed to come to an agreement. I hope that we will have very quickly an agreement also in the Council, so that these two pieces of legislation can go hand in hand and help us to create the security of supply across the board and in every Member State, because it is very clear also from this debate, the immense risk the shortages of critical medicines can create. And we have seen this already in the COVID crisis.\nNow, maybe to respond to one of the key issues that was mentioned here by Mr Sokol. And then there was an exchange between him and Mr WÃ¶lken about the stock planning. Just to make it very clear. We have clear provisions now so that when Member States are setting their own rules, when it comes to the security of supply, they will be required by this law to come forward with programmes and to communicate this to the Commission, but also to other Member states. And when they do that, they have to be mindful when defining the scope of which products are covered, but also in terms of the timings or the time periods necessary, that it has to be proportionate. It has to be done in a transparent and in a solid way so that they are not putting risks on other Member States. I think this is a topic which we have all seen during the COVID crisis, but it is a reoccurring one, and this is why we have included this in the proposal itself.\nNow, one of you also mentioned the issue of orphan drugs. I would also add the need for new antibiotics. This is why we have enlarged the scope of the act to cover all potential products, where we will have a critical need emerging so that we will be much faster to react to any problems on the market. And we will be able to deliver these products much faster.\nAnd finally, on the points raised by many about transparency. I think it is very clear that this Commission aims for full transparency when it comes to the implementation of this act. This is why joint procurement is the key tool through which we are going from where the conditions and costs are going to be public, as it is the case in any procurement. Same goes for the facilities created through the possibility of providing State aid for re-attracting manufacturing capacities in the EU. I think the State aid rules already have a very high level of transparency in the European Union."
      },
      {
        "@value": ""
      }
    ],
