    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#name": [
      {
        "@value": "Jaume Asens LlodrÃ"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "@id": "https://w3id.org/deliberation/resource/contribution_424",
    "@type": [
      "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#Contribution"
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#identifier": [
      {
        "@value": "contribution_424"
      }
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#madeBy": [
      {
        "@id": "https://w3id.org/deliberation/resource/participant_302"
      },
      {
        "@id": "https://w3id.org/deliberation/resource/participant_90"
      }
    ],
    "https://w3id.org/deliberation/ontology#text": [
      {
        "@value": "Mentre USA e Cina sovvenzionavano lâindustria noi avevano il Green Industrial Plan senza sussidi a sostenerlo, nÃ© disaccoppiamento del prezzo dell'elettricitÃ  dal gas, tanto per dirne qualcuna.\nE cianciamo ancora di Europa leader su questo ed Europa leader su questâaltro. Mentre siamo diventati gli ultimi e rischiamo di rimanerci.\nOggi di nuovo solo 100 miliardi sul piatto di finanziamenti giÃ  esistenti! Si potrebbe obiettare: non ci sono soldi. Poi, ecco arrivare ReArm Europe con 800 miliardi per la difesa. Ã il coniglio dal cilindro! Diventa chiaro che il vero piano industriale UE Ã¨ la conversione bellica, ovviamente a debito, a spese dei contribuenti. Magari con una nuova guerra, che alza sempre il PIL.\nAbbiate almeno il coraggio di dirlo apertamente ai vostri lettori!"
      },
      {
        "@value": "On this World Consumer Rights Day, Europe faces two big challenges due to the current geopolitical context. First, Europe is not the land of the rule of the strongest, but the place in which real laws are made to defend our citizens and consumers. But these laws must be enforced if we really want to protect the more vulnerable users, like minors or women, from online hate and cyberbullying, and also protect our democracies from disinformation. In front of any attempt at blackmail, the EU needs to choose its side. Either we defend the strongest – the big tech oligarchs who hate women, migrants and European democracy – or we protect European consumer rights. For me, the choice is clear.\nSecond, in the current context of trade wars, European consumers have the opportunity to defend European businesses by choosing products made in Europe. We are a market, or 440 million consumers. This is our strength, our leverage. Let's use it. So think global, buy local."
      }
    ],
